<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="12">
This remarkable new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copel" authorityYear="1932" class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="macrolepidota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris macrolepidota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Copel. (type from Tahiti), a species distinguished by it massive suberect rhizome with russet scales to 30 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm, fronds to 160 cm long, stipes to 50-70 cm long, stipes and rachises paleaceous with long, thin russet scales with dark, thickened bases, 3-pinnate subcoriaceous blades to 80 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
40 cm, the abaxial surfaces with scattered thin, linear scales, and supramedial sori. Society Islands collections in the Bishop Museum herbarium identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copel" authorityYear="1932" baseAuthorityName="Mett. ex Kuhn" class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="dicksonioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris dicksonioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Mett. ex Kuhn) Copel. have massive prostrate to erect rhizomes to 50 cm tall, fronds 80-140 cm long with stipes 60-100 cm long scaly only near the base, stipe scales dark brown and opaque to 20 mm long, rachises with small brown, scattered scales, and 3-pinnate-pinnatifid blades to 80 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
40 cm, the segments thinly chartaceous with linear brown scales on the lower surfaces. Scales of the rhizomes and stipe bases in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lorence &amp; W. L. Wagner" authorityYear="2011" class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="macropholis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris macropholis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are much larger than in the former two species. Palmer (2003) considered 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copel" authorityYear="1932" baseAuthorityName="Mett. ex Kuhn" class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="dicksonioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris dicksonioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
synonymous with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Brack." class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="glabra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris glabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Brack.) Kuntze, an exindusiate species endemic to the Hawaiian Islands. However, the type of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copel" authorityYear="1932" baseAuthorityName="Mett. ex Kuhn" class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="dicksonioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris dicksonioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is from Tahiti and clearly does not represent 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Brack." class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="glabra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris glabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Copeland, EB" journalOrPublisher="Bernice P. Bishop Museum Bulletin" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 86" refId="B11" refString="Copeland, EB, 1932. Pteridophytes of the Society Islands. Bernice P. Bishop Museum Bulletin 93: 1 - 86" title="Pteridophytes of the Society Islands" volume="93" year="1932">Copeland 1932</bibRefCitation>
). This new species seems most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lorence &amp; W. L. Wagner" authorityYear="2011" class="Pteridopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="Dryopteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Filicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="12" phylum="Polypodiophyta" rank="species" species="sweetorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="12">Dryopteris sweetorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, known only from Fatu Hiva, which differs by its rhizome and stipe base scales smaller, lustrous, dark brown, 9-25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 mm and its broadly ovate-deltate, 3-pinnate-pinnatifid blades (42
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)62–">-)62-</normalizedToken>
93 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(38
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)64–">-)64-</normalizedToken>
80 cm, the ultimate segments to 15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 mm, spaced 5-10 mm distant, oblique with tips acute, cut about halfway to the costule, with margins acutely serrate, and the abaxial surfaces and rachises glabrous.
</paragraph>
